## The task objective is to predict the species of an iris plant based on its petal and sepal dimensions.

## Known Characteristics of Iris Species:
### - Setosa (Iris setosa): typically has the smallest petal length, with an average length of about 1-2 cm, and a relatively small sepal to petal ratio. Petal width is generally small, around 0.5-1.5 cm.
### - Versicolor (Iris versicolor): has intermediate petal dimensions and a comparable sepal to petal ratio. Petal length is generally 1-4 cm, and petal width is around 0.5-2 cm.
### - Virginica (Iris virginica): has the largest petal length, with an average length of about 4-7 cm, and the largest sepal to petal ratio. Petal width is generally 2-4 cm.

## Common Characteristics and Their Implications:
### - Short and narrow petal dimensions (petal length < 2 cm, petal width < 1 cm) are more common in Iris setosa.
### - Short and narrow petal dimensions combined with relatively long sepal dimensions (sepal length > 5 cm) are more common in Iris versicolor.
### - Relatively long petal and sepal dimensions (petal length > 4 cm, sepal length > 5 cm) are more common in Iris virginica.

## Task Strategy:
### The task strategy involves comparing the input petal and sepal dimensions to the known characteristics of Iris species and utilizing the common characteristics to make a prediction.

## Evaluation Criteria:
### The task will be evaluated based on the accuracy of the prediction. The predicted species will be considered accurate if it matches the actual species of the iris plant.

## Note:
### The task is sensitive to the input petal and sepal dimensions. Small variations in the dimensions can significantly impact the prediction.

## Additional Notes:
### - The classification of iris species is primarily based on the petal and sepal dimensions.
### - While sepal length is an important factor in distinguishing between the three species, sepal width is also a relevant characteristic.
### - Iris setosa is typically characterized by small petal dimensions and a small sepal to petal ratio.
### - Iris versicolor is typically characterized by intermediate petal dimensions and a comparable sepal to petal ratio.
### - Iris virginica is typically characterized by large petal dimensions and a large sepal to petal ratio.
### - The task may involve multiple iterations to achieve high accuracy, as the input dimensions may not always fit neatly into one category.
### - It is essential to consider both the petal and sepal dimensions when making a prediction, as the two characteristics are interconnected and complement each other.
