### - Short and narrow petal dimensions (petal length < 2 cm, petal width < 1 cm) are more common in Iris setosa.
### - Short and narrow petal dimensions combined with relatively long sepal dimensions (sepal length > 5 cm) are more common in Iris versicolor.
### - Relatively long petal and sepal dimensions (petal length > 4 cm, sepal length > 5 cm) are more common in Iris virginica.

## Task Strategy:
### The task strategy involves comparing the input petal and sepal dimensions to the known characteristics of Iris species and utilizing the common characteristics to make a prediction.

## Evaluation Criteria:
### The task will be evaluated based on the accuracy of the prediction. The predicted species will be considered accurate if it matches the actual species of the iris plant.

## Note:
### The task is sensitive to the input petal and sepal dimensions. Small variations in the dimensions can significantly impact the prediction.

## Additional Tips for the Assistant:
### When comparing the input dimensions to the characteristics of Iris species, consider the following factors:
### - The sepal to petal ratio: Iris versicolor typically has a comparable sepal to petal ratio, while Iris virginica has the largest sepal to petal ratio. Iris setosa has a relatively small sepal to petal ratio.
### - The petal width: Iris setosa tends to have smaller petal widths, while Iris virginica tends to have larger petal widths.
### - The combination of short and narrow petal dimensions with long sepal dimensions: This combination is more characteristic of Iris versicolor.
### - The combination of relatively long petal and sepal dimensions: This combination is more characteristic of Iris virginica.
